    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a lineup optimized for stolen base efficiency and favorable matchups against moderate pitching. Our clear offensive anchor is **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98), whose matchup against Kelly provides the highest ceiling of the day. The combination of an elite 18% boost from the opposing pitcher\u2019s skill and a massive 14% dynamic platoon advantage makes him an essential start, despite a lower batting order position. **Junior Caminero** (73.06) also profiles as a high-upside play; while park factors slightly penalize his outing, his projection is buoyed by a significant 15% SP skill advantage against Mahle, making him our most reliable non-leadoff bat. **Trea Turner** (69.27) remains the engine of our SB strategy, maintaining a strong score despite the park and platoon headwinds, primarily driven by his leadoff priority and Paddack\u2019s susceptibility to stolen bases.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench involved **Jerar Encarnacion** (42.40), who sat just outside the efficiency cutoff. While his platoon advantage against Matz offered potential, his projected floor ultimately couldn\u2019t displace the higher-upside profiles of **Colt Keith** (65.83) or **Carson Benge** (64.59). The optimizer favored **Colt Keith** specifically due to a rare convergence of park factors and the pitcher\u2019s slow delivery, which increases the likelihood of SB opportunities\u2014a crucial metric for the Zebras. Conversely, **Josh Smith** (38.97) failed to meet our 40.0 baseline, falling victim to a significant 15% penalty from the L/L platoon matchup. We remain cautious regarding **Yordan Alvarez** (60.46) as he faces a tough lefty in Suarez; while his talent profile is elite, the platoon penalty significantly suppresses his raw efficiency compared to his usual output. We continue to monitor the IL status of **Christian Yelich**, while **Luke Raley** remains sidelined today, ensuring we maintain strict adherence to our game cap management.",
